---

<Base
  title="Genome browser integration — JBrowseMSA"
  description="Use react-msaview inside JBrowse 2 — an MSA viewer with a tree beside genome annotation, DNA-alignment tracks, and protein↔genome coordinate sync, driven entirely by declarative URLs."
  wide
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>In the genome browser</h1>
    <p>
      react-msaview ships as a JBrowse 2 plugin
      (<a href="https://github.com/GMOD/jbrowse-plugin-msaview">jbrowse-plugin-msaview</a>), so the
      same viewer — alignment, phylogenetic tree, and all — runs as a view <em>inside</em> JBrowse,
      stacked alongside a Linear Genome View with gene annotation and multiple-alignment tracks.
      Every view here is opened by a <strong>declarative link</strong>: the whole multi-view session
      lives in the URL, with nothing to install or set up.
    </p>

    <h2 id="combined-view">A combined view: factor XII lost in whales</h2>
    <p>
      The link below opens one JBrowse view with two panels. On top, a Linear Genome View of the
      human <strong>F12</strong> locus (coagulation factor XII) showing the NCBI RefSeq gene track and
      a UCSC Multiz mammalian DNA alignment. Below, the react-msaview panel: the F12 coding alignment
      across mammals with its inferred tree.
    </p>
    <p>
      F12 is intact across land mammals and in the semi-aquatic hippopotamus, but is
      <strong>disabled by frameshifts and premature stop codons in cetaceans</strong> — whales,
      dolphins and porpoises — one of many genes lost in the transition to fully aquatic life. The
      tree groups the cetaceans together (with hippo as their closest relative), and a single shared
      frameshift is visible in the alignment. It is exactly the cross-species, nucleotide-level
      evidence an MSA <em>editor</em> would let you curate and lift over to many species.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.combined} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the combined view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img
        src={`${base}/media/f12-combined-view.png`}
        alt="JBrowse combined view: F12 gene track and Multiz mammal alignment above a react-msaview panel with a phylogenetic tree"
      />
      <figcaption>
        F12 on hg38 — gene track + Multiz 470-way mammal alignment, above the react-msaview panel
        (coding alignment + tree). One declarative URL.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="linked-src">A linked protein view: SRC, beside its gene</h2>
    <p>
      The combined view above is two <em>independent</em> panels. The MSA viewer can also be
      <strong>connected</strong> to the genome view so the two share coordinates. This link opens the
      human <strong>SRC</strong> proto-oncogene on hg38 beside the Src-family kinase alignment (with
      its tree), connected through the SRC transcript model:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Click a residue in the alignment → the genome view navigates to that residue's codon.</li>
      <li>Hover the gene in the genome view → the corresponding alignment column highlights.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The mapping runs through the codon structure of the transcript, so it is a true
      protein-to-nucleotide link rather than a side-by-side approximation. SRC is the prototypical
      tyrosine-kinase proto-oncogene, with the SH3 / SH2 / kinase domain architecture the family is
      named for.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.proteinLinked} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the linked SRC protein view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="braf-v600e">Zoomed on a mutation: BRAF V600E</h2>
    <p>
      The same connected pattern, opened on a single codon. This link puts the human
      <strong>BRAF</strong> proto-oncogene on hg38 beside the RAF-family kinase alignment, with the
      genome view positioned right on the <strong>V600</strong> codon (highlighted in the genome) and
      the matching alignment column pre-highlighted across every sequence. The gene track is collapsed
      to BRAF's single longest coding transcript and the reference sequence is coloured by codon frame,
      so at this base-level zoom the V600 codon reads cleanly in-frame beside the alignment. A
      <strong>ClinVar pathogenic-variant track</strong> stacks the known disease alleles directly onto
      that codon.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>V600E</strong> — a single <code>c.1799T&gt;A</code> change at
      <code>chr7:140,753,336</code> that swaps valine for glutamate — is the most common oncogenic
      mutation in melanoma and a recurrent driver in colorectal and thyroid cancer, hairy-cell
      leukemia and others. V600 sits in the kinase <em>activation segment</em>, and the alignment shows
      why the position matters: the valine is <strong>invariant</strong> down the RAF family and across
      human, mouse, chicken and fly, so the highlighted column is solid. Because the views are
      connected through the BRAF transcript model, the lit alignment column and the highlighted genome
      base are the very same residue — click the column and the genome stays locked on the V600E codon,
      where the ClinVar track shows V600E (<code>c.1799T&gt;A</code>) amid a pileup of other pathogenic
      V600 alleles.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the protein the <a href="https://github.com/GMOD/proteinbrowser">proteinbrowser</a> demos
      center on, here as a self-contained declarative link with the biology made explicit.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.brafV600} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the BRAF V600E view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="tp53-r248">Conservation meets pathogenicity: TP53 R248</h2>
    <p>
      The BRAF link shows one mutation; this one shows a whole clinical archive landing on a single
      conserved column. It opens the human <strong>TP53</strong> tumour suppressor on hg38 — with a
      <strong>ClinVar pathogenic-variant track</strong> — beside an alignment of p53 across thirteen
      vertebrates (human to zebrafish), connected and positioned on the <strong>R248</strong> codon.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>R248</strong> is the single most frequently mutated residue in TP53 across human cancers.
      It reaches into the DNA minor groove to let p53 bind its targets, so substitutions there abolish
      function. In the genome view a dense wall of distinct ClinVar pathogenic variants stacks onto the
      three bases of the R248 codon; in the alignment directly below, the highlighted column reads
      <code>R</code> in every species — <strong>invariant for ~430 million years</strong>. The
      conserved column and the pathogenic pileup are the same position, viewed through evolution and
      through the clinic at once. (ClinVar is updated weekly, so the exact variant count drifts over
      time.)
    </p>

    <p>
      <a class="cta" href={links.tp53R248} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Open the TP53 R248 view in JBrowse →
      </a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="how-built">How the links are built</h2>
    <p>
      Each link is a JBrowse
      <a href="https://jbrowse.org/jb2/docs/urlparams/#session-spec">session spec</a>:
      <code>?config=…&amp;session=spec-&#123;"views":[…]&#125;</code>, where each entry launches a view
      — a <code>LinearGenomeView</code> with its assembly, location and tracks, and an
      <code>MsaView</code> pointed at an alignment file. To <em>connect</em> the two (the SRC
      example), the genome view is given an explicit <code>id</code> and the <code>MsaView</code>
      carries a <code>connectedViewId</code> referencing it, plus a <code>connectedFeature</code> —
      the transcript model used for the protein↔genome codon mapping — and a <code>querySeqName</code>
      naming the matching row in the alignment. A <code>highlightColumns</code> array (the BRAF and
      TP53 examples) seeds the highlighted-column overlay so a link can open with specific columns lit;
      <code>colorByCDS</code> on the genome view colours the reference by codon frame; and the
      <code>tracks</code> entries can carry per-track display overrides (the gene track is collapsed to
      its longest coding transcript with <code>geneGlyphMode: "longestCoding"</code>) plus extra tracks
      such as the BRAF and TP53 ClinVar variant tracks. Those transcript models are derived reproducibly
      from the public RefSeq annotation by the generators under <code>scripts/</code>
      (<code>src-protein-link</code>, <code>braf-protein-link</code>, <code>tp53-protein-link</code>); the
      BRAF and TP53 directories also carry <code>build-*</code> scripts that regenerate the alignment,
      tree and ClinVar variant data from their public sources. A view loaded from a cross-origin config
      asks you to trust the plugin once before it renders.
    </p>
